<br>
After a few moments, the pain subsided in his head.  He blinked his eyes open, unsure of his surroundings.  He was in a small room, on the floor, next to a bed.  His clothing and armor were scattered about, furniture overturned.  There were a few flasks that were empty strewn about as well.  Then it all came back to him.  He was in Thurgardin.  He was in the room that Fenwyn and he had shared many of their intimate moments with each other.  A brief smile touched his lips..then he remembered.<br>
<br>
He struck her.  Rather..his body struck her as he could only watch sadly, crying out for the evil one to stop.  His beloved Fenwyn.  Seeing her in such a way, seeing her succumb to the dark elf broke his heart.  Feeling his body strike her, fighting as hard as he could, but not able to win.  His Fenwyn.  <br>
<br>
Hakkin the dwarf's eyes shed their tears freely, his head now in his hands.  How could he have ever let this happen.  How could he have allowed the dark elf to take over?  His Fenwyn.  How could she ever forgive him.<br>
<br>
&quot;You weak, pathetic being,&quot; the dark voice hissed in his mind, bringing with it pain.  &quot;No wonder I win so easily.  You have turned into nothing but a drunkard, a weak willed nobody.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Shut up,&quot; Hakkin the dwarf said, but it was a weak attempt.  All he could see was Fenwyn's face, the pain and the hurt in her eyes.  The dark elf knew this, and kept replaying it over in his mind, laughing.  <br>
<br>
Hakkin the dwarf stood up, staggered over to his bags, muttering, then finding what he was looking for.  He pulled the cork from the bottle, then tipped it back, draining it.  <br>
<br>
Soon, his mind became numb, then blackness, the laughter echoing into the darkness... <p><br>
