<br>
She tried not to notice the dwarven inkeeper sighing and shaking his head at her as she brought up food and drink for her beloved.  <br>
<br>
How she loathed the look that the Coldain in the inn gave her, it was a look of disappointment, sadness...and pity.  Pity because no doubt they saw how dejected she was, but perhaps the walls were thinner than she thought.  She had tried not to cry out, but it seemed that even as she tried to keep silent, the master was spurred even more to make her do so.<br>
<br>
She paused at the door, trembling in a disgusting mix of fear, yearning and anticipation.  Then, for a moment, she thought that she heard Hakkin, the dwarf's voice, and her hopes jumped.  Perhaps..perhaps he had returned!<br>
<br>
Quickly, she opened the door, her smile and hopes exhultant, just in time to see the shimmer of the magics that would remove the dwarf that she loved and held so dear, to be replaced by the cruel dark elf visage that she feared. <br>
<br>
The figure was laughing as he tipped another bottle of liqour into his mouth; beckoning her to enter.<br>
<br>
